<section class="page-section">
  <h2>AI Engineering Roadmap</h2>
  <p>I'm a software engineer with a background in cloud data engineering (Java, Python, GCP stack), and I'm currently pursuing UT Austin's online MSAI program (Fall 2026 start, targeting May 2028 graduation).</p>
  <p>
    This page exists for one reason: to hold myself accountable in
    public. If I fall behind, you'll know.
  </p>
  <p>
    My goal is to expand my data/cloud engineering path toward
    production-focused ML Engineering and AI Infrastructure work. I'm
    not trying to abandon data engineering or become an ML researcher.
    I want to apply the pipeline, cloud, and systems experience I
    already have to build and implement AI solutions for real business
    use cases, then run those systems in production at scale for real
    users.
  </p>
  <p>Here's the plan, broken into three phases.</p>

  <h2>Phase 1: Foundation</h2>
  <p>
    Now through Summer 2027. Theme: bridge the gap between data
    engineering and ML engineering.
  </p>
  <p>
    At work, my current role is not ML/AI-focused, so my near-term
    target is to grow as a mid-senior software engineer: strengthen
    system design, improve engineering processes, own services end to
    end, and practice architectural thinking. Those skills are the base
    I need before adding ML Engineering and AI Infrastructure on top.
  </p>
  <p>Milestones I'm committing to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Complete pre-program self-study: PyTorch fundamentals, linear
      algebra review (Deisenroth et al.), and UT's Deep Learning
      course materials
    </li>
    <li>
      Build and deploy at least one production-grade ML project (not a
      notebook, not a tutorial clone): Dockerized, tested, API-served,
      monitored
    </li>
    <li>
      Start writing publicly about ML engineering patterns, what I'm
      learning, and where data engineering meets ML infrastructure
    </li>
    <li>
      Contribute to at least one open-source ML infrastructure project
      (MLflow, Ray, vLLM, or similar)
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    What success looks like: by the end of this phase, my GitHub and
    writing should make it obvious I build ML systems, not just train
    models.
  </p>

  <h2>Phase 2: Depth and Proof</h2>
  <p>
    Fall 2027 through May 2028. Theme: go deep in coursework and build
    undeniable proof of competence.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is the heaviest stretch of the MSAI program. Deep Learning,
    NLP, ML foundations, and Ethics all land in this window. The goal
    isn't just to pass. It's to come out of each course with something
    deployable.
  </p>
  <p>Milestones I'm committing to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Maintain strong standing across all foundational courses</li>
    <li>
      Build a capstone-quality project that demonstrates end-to-end ML
      system design (data ingestion, training pipeline, serving,
      monitoring, user-facing interface)
    </li>
    <li>
      Have a portfolio of 2-3 deployed projects that show range: NLP,
      computer vision, or recommendation systems, each with production
      characteristics
    </li>
    <li>
      Sharpen algorithms fundamentals — LeetCode, system design
      thinking, ML-specific patterns. Keeps the problem-solving sharp
      and complements the coursework
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    What success looks like: by graduation, I should be able to
    design and build ML systems end-to-end, not just train models
    in notebooks.
  </p>

  <h2>Phase 3: Apply and Grow</h2>
  <p>
    Summer 2028 through 2031. Theme: apply everything I've learned
    and grow into a senior-level AI/ML engineer.
  </p>
  <p>
    With the MSAI complete and a strong portfolio in hand, this is
    where the learning compounds. The goal is to own the full ML
    lifecycle — from model development through deployment and
    production monitoring — wherever that takes me.
  </p>
  <p>Milestones I'm committing to:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Own or significantly contribute to at least one production ML
      system end-to-end
    </li>
    <li>
      Continue publishing technical writing and open-source
      contributions to build reputation in the ML engineering
      community
    </li>
    <li>
      By 2031, be operating at a senior level where I'm designing ML
      systems, mentoring others, and influencing technical direction
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    What success looks like: by 2031, "ML Engineer" isn't just a
    title. It's what I demonstrably am, backed by systems in
    production and a body of public work.
  </p>

  <h2>How to Hold Me Accountable</h2>
  <p>
    I'll update this page quarterly with progress. If a milestone
    slips, I'll say why. No vague excuses, no silent edits. The whole
    point of posting this publicly is that I can't hide from it.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you're on a similar path, feel free to reach out. If you're
    ahead of me, I'd love to learn from you.
  </p>
  <p>Last updated: May 2026</p>
</section>
